Mark Zuckerberg says the workers will be in addition to the 4,500 who already review posts that may violate its terms of service. JOHANNESBURG - Facebook will add 3,000 people over the next year to monitor reports of inappropriate material on the social media network and removing videos such as murders and suicides.Chief executive officer Mark Zuckerberg says the workers will be in addition to the 4,500 people who already review posts that may violate its terms of service.The hiring spree represents an acknowledgement by Facebook that, at least for now, it needs more than automated software to improve monitoring of broadcasts on Facebook live - which is a service that has been marred since its launch last year by instances of people streaming violence.In the latest incident, police said a Thai man filmed himself killing his 11-month-old daughter in two video clips posted on Facebook before committing suicide.The videos were accessible from the father's Facebook page for roughly 24 hours, until they were taken down in Bangkok.Facebook had earlier said it would review how it monitors violent footage and other objectionable material in response to the killing after Stephens' post was visible on the social media site for about two hours.Zuckerberg said on Facebook post: These reviewers will also help us get better at removing things we don't allow on Facebook like hate speech and child exploitation. And we'll keep working with local community groups and law enforcement who are in the best position to help someone if they need it - either because they're about to harm themselves, or because they're in danger from someone else. He says the social media network is also building better tools to keep its community safe. We re going to make it simpler to report problems to us, faster for our reviewers to determine which posts violate our standards and easier for them contact law enforcement if someone needs help. According to the CEO and co-founder, Facebook reviewers were able to assist in stopping a suicide last week.Over the last few weeks, we've seen people hurting themselves and others on Facebook -- either live or in video posted...